                <p class="about4">WHO MAY REGISTER?</p>
                 <h1 class="about5">Voter registration is open to eligible citizens of legal voting age within a given jurisdiction. Eligibility requirements may vary, but typically include citizenship and a minimum age, enabling individuals to participate in the democratic process by exercising their right to vote.    
                </h1>
                <p class="about4">WHO ARE DISQUALIFIED?</p>
                <h1 class="about5">1. Those who have lost their Filipino citizenship in accordance with Philippine laws;</h1>
                <h1 class="about5">2. Those who have expressly renounced their Philippine citizenship or have pledged
                            allegiance to a foreign country, except dual citizens as referred to under RA 9225 </h1>
                <h1 class="about5">3. Those who have committed/are convicted in a final judgment by court or tribunal of an
                            offense punishable by imprisonment of not less than one (1) year;</h1>
                <h1 class="about5">4. Any citizen of the Philippines abroad previously declared insane or incompetent by
                            competent authority in the Philippines of abroad.</h1>

                <p class="about4">REQUIREMENTS FOR REGISTRATION</p>
                <h1 class="about5">Applicants are required to bring the following:</h1>
                <h1 class="about5">1. Age: the minimum voting age is typically 18 years old in the Philippines. Some states allow individuals who will turn 18 by the time of the next general election to register in advance.</h1>
                <h1 class="about5">2. Residency: You must be a resident of the state in which you want to register to vote. You generally need to provide a residential address.</h1>
                <h1 class="about5">3. Name and Address: The information you provide on your registration form must be accurate and consistent with other official records.</h1>
                <h1 class="about5">4. Identification: While some states require a photo ID to vote, registering to vote often does not require one. However, having identification can be useful for verifying your identity.</h1>
